## What's Wayground?

Wayground (formerly Quizizz) is an education platform helping teachers drive student outcomes with tools to create content like assessments & lessons, track student understanding, content libraries and more.

Our assessments tool supports around 20+ question types, and our premium plan gives access to premium question types like Labeling, in addition to unlimited assessment creation.

## Problem statement

We wanted to improve the creation and consumption experience of premium question types across the platform, so that teachers build trust in our premium offering.

{% sidenote %}
QT is a cute shorthand for question type we use internally.
{% /sidenote %}

We started with Labeling QT as, 
1. It was commonly used by science, biology and social studies teachers (good chunk of our user base).
2. It had the highest drop off rates of all premium question type creation experience.

## How Labeling QT works
Labeling is used to ask questions like "label the parts of a flower" or "Annotate the map with landmarks", and students have to drag the appropriate labels onto the blanks on the image.

![image-1](/case-studies/labeling/labeling-working.webp)

## What wasn't working

The old creation experience was a WYSIWYG-style that teachers found difficult to use. Through hotjar recordings, conversations with teachers and analytics data, we narrowed it down to the following,

{% figure src="/case-studies/labeling/problems.png" alt="image of problems" noStroke=true width="wide" /%}

Let's explore how we addressed these issues.

## Using vision models to accelerate question creation

We wanted to reduce the time taken to create a labeling question using LLMs but throwing a prompt box at the teacher didn't feel right, It's 2024 and they were still kinda getting used to prompting. 

Also, image generation is expensive and teachers generally have an image in mind before they start creating a labeling question. Can we rather help them select an image and generate questions with labels?

We prototyped various flows before arriving at the following pipeline.

![image-2](/case-studies/labeling/pipeline.webp)

It's simple and effective.
1. Teachers select an image on Wayground. 
2. We analyse the image and suggest questions that can be asked on the image
3. Teachers can pick a generated question and we add labels automatically, or they can create their own question and labels.

{% accordion title="Handling hallucinations and label positioning" subtitle="Click to read more about this" %}

The questions and labels generated by the model had to be, 
1. Diverse, with varying levels of difficulty to capture a wide range of teacher intent.
2. Accurate, with the model generating correct labels for a given image.
3. Positioned correctly on the image (the most difficult part)

LLMs hallucinated a lot when asked to share coordinates of labels directly. I added some abstraction by chopping the image into a 5x5 grid and asking it to share (x,y) position in the grid instead, which performed better but was still unreliable. 

[image of grid breakdown approach]

So for V1 (2024) we simply provided all labels asked the teacher to reposition them. 

A few months ago we updated the pipeline to use Nano Banana Pro, which gave accurate label positions.
{% /accordion %}

{% lottie src="/lottie/Labelling.json" label="Image-first Labeling question creation flow" caption="We built a neat interaction to quickly glance at labels generated for each question." loop=true autoplay=true controls=false width="wide" caption="Interactions for question selection and label previews."/%}

## Label creation experience

LLMs aren't perfect and teachers should be able to edit labels and make final adjustments. So we revamped our editor and the label creation experience. 

We also added a label orientation setting that gives further positional control over the labels, helpful when students have to annotate two or more labels close to each other.

{% labelCreationBento /%}

## Impact

The redesign meaningfully improved the creation experience for Labeling.

- Question save rate increased from 48–52% to 75%.
- Average creation time reduced from around 8 mins to 5.5–6 mins.
- AI suggestions were accepted about 1 in 3 times.
- Labeling became a great sales demo of AI being deeply integrated into product workflow.

This case study is a basic overview, not an end-to-end deep dive.
